:::summary
Pericles (c. 495–429 BC) was the greatest statesman of ancient Athens — the architect of Athenian democracy and the patron of the remarkable cultural flowering known as the Golden Age of Athens. Under his leadership, Athens built the Parthenon, cultivated philosophy, drama, and history, and became the intellectual fountainhead of Western civilization.
:::

